  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "How do you avoid a girl without hurting her, who is madly in love with you?",
  "response": "Navigating a situation where someone has strong feelings for you, but you don\u2019t feel the same way, can be sensitive. Here are some steps you can take to handle this situation with care:\n\n1. **Be Honest but Kind**: It\u2019s important to communicate your feelings honestly. Let her know that you value her as a person but do not feel the same way romantically. Be clear, but gentle in your explanation.\n\n2. **Choose the Right Setting**: Have the conversation in a private, comfortable setting where she can process her feelings without added pressure or embarrassment.\n\n3. **Use \u201cI\u201d Statements**: Focus on your own feelings. For example, say \u201cI don\u2019t feel a romantic connection\u201d instead of \u201cYou\u2019re not my type.\u201d This helps to reduce any feelings of rejection.\n\n4. **Acknowledge Her Feelings**: Recognize and validate her feelings. Let her know that it\u2019s okay to have feelings for someone and that it\u2019s a natural part of life.\n\n5. **Set Boundaries**: After the conversation, it might be helpful to set clear boundaries to help both of you move on. This might mean spending less time together or changing the nature of your interactions.\n\n6. **Give Her Space**: After your conversation, allow her some space to process her feelings. This is vital for both her healing and your own.\n\n7. **Be Supportive but Stay Firm**: If she wants to talk about her feelings afterward, be supportive, but remain firm in your decision. It\u2019s important not to give mixed signals.\n\n8. **Encourage Personal Growth**: If appropriate, encourage her to focus on her own interests and friendships. This can help her to move on and build her self-esteem outside of this relationship.\n\n9. **Seek Mutual Support**: If you have mutual friends, be aware that it can be hard for them to navigate the situation. Consider discussing how you can both maintain friends without awkwardness.\n\n10. **Be Ready for a Range of Reactions**: Understand that she may feel hurt, angry, or sad, and allow her to express those emotions. Everyone processes rejection differently.\n\nRemember, while you want to avoid hurting her feelings, being truthful is ultimately the kindest approach in the long run.",
